Consider two waves given by:
\begin{align*}
    y_1 &= A \sin(kx - \omega t), \\
    y_2 &= A \sin(kx - \omega t + \delta).
\end{align*}

The resultant wave is:
\begin{align*}
    y &= y_1 + y_2 \\
      &= A \left[ \sin(kx - \omega t) + \sin(kx - \omega t + \delta) \right] \\
      &= 2A \cos \left( \frac{\delta}{2} \right) \sin \left( kx - \omega t + \frac{\delta}{2} \right).
\end{align*}

Thus, the amplitude of the resultant wave is \(2A \cos \left( \frac{\delta}{2} \right)\).

For \(A = 6 \, \text{cm}\) and \(\delta = \frac{\pi}{2}\), the amplitude of the resultant wave will be:
\[
2 \times 6 \cos \frac{\pi}{4} = 6\sqrt{2} \, \text{cm}.
\]

For \(2A \cos \left( \frac{\delta}{2} \right) = 6\), we have:
\[
\cos \left( \frac{\delta}{2} \right) = \frac{6}{2A} = \frac{6}{2 \times 6} = \frac{1}{2} = \cos \frac{\pi}{3}.
\]

Therefore, \(\frac{\delta}{2} = \frac{\pi}{3}\) or \(\delta = \frac{2\pi}{3}\).

If two sound waves with slightly different frequencies are produced, then beats are heard. These consist of regular swelling and fading of the sound. In one set of waves, compressions and rarefactions will be spaced further apart, while in another they will be close enough. At some instant, two compressions arrive together at the ear of the listener, and the sound is loud. At a later time, the compression of one wave arrives with the rarefaction of the other, and the sound will be faint. Beats are thus caused due to the interference of sound waves of neighboring frequencies in time. The beat frequency is equal to the difference \(f_1 - f_2\) for the two component waves. Beats between two tones can be detected by the ear up to a frequency of about 7/s.

