The natural frequencies for a rod free at both ends are given by:
\[
f_n = \frac{n}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{Y}{\rho}} \quad (n=1,2,3,\ldots)
\]

\subsubsection*{(ii) Rod Clamped at the Midpoint}

The natural frequencies for a rod clamped at the midpoint are given by:
\[
f_n = \frac{n}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{Y}{\rho}} \quad (n=1,3,5,\ldots)
\]

\subsubsection*{(iii) Bar Clamped at Both Ends (Fixed–Fixed)}

The natural frequencies for a bar clamped at both ends are given by:
\[
f_n = \frac{n}{2L} \sqrt{\frac{Y}{\rho}} \quad (n=1,2,3,\ldots)
\]

\subsection*{Discussion}

For case (a) (bar clamped at one end only), the frequency of the fundamental is half that of a similar free–free (case (b) (i)) or fixed–fixed (case (b) (iii)) bar, and only the odd-numbered harmonic overtones are present. This is expected since clamping a free–free bar at its center suppresses all its even harmonics.

For case (b) (ii) (rod clamped at the midpoint), only odd partials are present, similar to case (a) (fixed–free), and it differs from case (b) (i) (free–free) where all the partials are present. However, the fundamental has the same frequency in cases (b) (ii) and (b) (i).

